This rejection of aging as a fountain of youth can manifest in several ways. Some individuals may engage in excessive cosmetic procedures or beauty treatments, hoping to maintain a youthful appearance. Others may become fixated on staying up-to-date with the latest trends, fashion, and technologies, associating them with youth and vitality. Additionally, some young people may resist taking on adult responsibilities or commitments, clinging to a carefree and unburdened lifestyle.

While these responses may offer temporary relief from the fear of aging, it's important to recognize that they are based on misconceptions. Aging is a natural part of life, and no one can escape its effects entirely. Rejecting or denying the aging process ultimately hinders personal growth and acceptance of oneself. Embracing the idea of getting older and focusing on developing a positive mindset about the various stages of life can lead to a more fulfilling and content existence.

While I don't personally agree with Vivek Ramaswamy's proposition, it does bring to light some important discussions about civic duty and the responsibilities that come with the right to vote.

It seems to be a response to concerns about civic literacy and engagement. The idea of a civics test, for instance, is likely aimed at ensuring informed voting. But, the question is whether restricting voting rights is the best way to achieve this.

Your comparison to gun ownership is thought-provoking. Some might argue that just as we require training and licensing to own and operate firearms, we might also want to ensure voters are informed.
